{{Quote|A meter-tall stack of the worst business decisions you could possibly want.|''[[Mechtech Illustrated/Legends|Mechtech Illustrated]]'', criticizing the R5-series|<ref name="NEGTD">''[[The New Essential Guide to Droids]]''</ref>}}
The '''R5-series astromech droid''', also known as the '''R2-5''', was a line of low-cost [[Astromech droid/Legends|astromech droids]] built by [[Industrial Automaton/Legends|Industrial Automaton]]. Based upon the success of prior astromech models, such as the wildly popular [[R2-series astromech droid/Legends|R2-series]], Industrial Automaton intended the R5-series to cater to budget buyers at the cost of some functionality.

==Description==
The R5-series [[Astromech droid/Legends|astromech]] followed the standard [[R-series/Legends|R-series]] design, with a barrel-shaped body shell and three [[Tread|treaded]] legs.<ref name="EGTD" /> The [[Droid/Legends|droid's]] head was an [[R2n Agromech Head]]<ref name="DroidWorks">''[[Star Wars: DroidWorks]]''</ref> which was likened to a "flowerpot", and the [[radar eye]] that was present on previous models was replaced with three small [[Photoreceptor/Legends|photoreceptors]].<ref name="EGTD" />

[[File:R5schematics-EGTD.jpg|thumb|left|180px|R5-series schematics]]
Each droid had a heavy [[Grasper arm/Legends|grasper]] with a twenty-five [[Kilogram/Legends|kilogram]] lifting capacity, and a fine [[Manipulator arm/Legends|manipulator arm]] that had a placement accuracy of less than one [[micrometer]]. Standard equipment included a [[Holoprojector/Legends|holoprojector]], [[Arc welder/Legends|arc welder]], [[Circular saw/Legends|circular saw]], and a [[Fire extinguisher/Legends|fire extinguisher]].<ref name="EGTD" />

Industrial Automaton insisted on cutting corners in the R5's design, resulting in the unit's [[Behavioral circuitry matrix/Legends|behavioral circuitry matrix]] being prone to glitches over time, leading to droids developing caustic, disagreeable,<ref name="EGTD" /> and quirky personality.<ref name="AEG" /> R5s were capable of holding coordinates for only a single [[Hyperspace/Legends|hyperspace]] jump in their [[RAM|active memory]].<ref name="EGTD" /> The droid was also not tough enough to survive in harsh environments such as the [[Outer Rim Territories/Legends|Outer Rim Territories]].<ref name="AEG" />

==Role==
The R5-series was put into production by Industrial Automaton president [[Julynn Kentas]] in an attempt to cash in on the popularity of the company's R2-series.<ref name="J7">{{JournalCite|7|The History of R-Series Astromech Droids}}</ref> It was commissioned with no clear market or functionality in mind,<ref name="EGTD" /> and without any market testing to see if the droid-buying public wanted or needed a new model of astromech. The concept was to create an economy version of the R2,<ref name="J7" /> but the R5 lacked the versatility and "can-do" attitude that was the hallmark of the previous model. Essentially, Industrial Automaton created a new droid series not because of market demand, but because they could.<ref name="EGTD" />

==History==
Hundreds of thousands of R5 units were produced and sold<ref name="AEG" /> but the line was unpopular and a marketing failure.<ref name="J7" /> ''[[Mechtech Illustrated/Legends|Mechtech Illustrated]]'' called the R5 "a meter-tall stack of the worst business decisions you could possibly want."<ref name="NEGTD" /> The defining trait of the R5-series was its cheapness. While droid dealers attempted to promote the unit as the least expensive astromech on the market, the consumers who bought it decried it as an inferior product that was not worth half the price.<ref name="EGTD" />

Complaints about the droid flooded in to Industrial Automaton, with common issues being chronic overheating, jammed [[Servomotor/Legends|servos]], loose bearings, and blown [[Motivator/Legends|motivators]]. The first quarter sales figures were dismal, followed by several lamentable sales seasons.<ref name="EGTD" /> After a particularly poor sales [[Galactic Standard Calendar|year]], Industrial Automaton discontinued the R5 series in [[23 BBY/Legends|23 BBY]].<ref name="Hnn">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|45|business/13228_3.html|IA Pulls R5's Plug}}</ref> The R5 was Industrial Automaton's first flop in the astromech droid market, serving as a wake-up call to the company and the droid industry as a whole.<ref name="EGTD" /> In an attempt to recoup some of its losses, Industrial Automaton reused the R5 body shell in its [[R4 astromech droid/Legends|R4-series]] and [[R2-AG agromech droid]]s.<ref name="J7" />

During the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], members of the R5-series were used by the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Republic]] for a variety of roles, including use aboard [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighters]] like the [[Aggressive ReConnaissance-170 starfighter/Legends|ARC-170]] and [[Capital ship/Legends|capital ships]] like the [[Acclamator-class transgalactic military assault ship/Legends|''Acclamator''-class assault ship]].{{Fact}}

Some droids fell in to the hands of various pirate groups, such as the [[Ohnaka Gang/Legends|Ohnaka Gang]], who fitted weapons such as [[Blaster/Legends|blasters]] to their domes.{{Fact}}

[[File:R5astromechs_btm.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Two black R5 units on the Death Star]]
By the time of the [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]], R5 droids could be bought in bulk for a very low cost. The [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Alliance to Restore the Republic]] procured a large number of R5s to use as [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighter]] counterparts despite the fact that they could only hold a single set of hyperspace coordinates in their [[RAM|active memory]]. Alliance [[Technician/Legends|technicians]] embarked on a refit program that allowed them to modify their R5s with increased memory capacity that gave the droids the ability to hold six, seven, or even ten hyperspace coordinates. Despite this success, the R5s still had personality problems and a number of [[Pilot/Legends|pilots]] disliked the "flowerpot" head as it offered a larger target profile for the enemy.<ref name="EGTD" />

One R5 unit in particular, [[R5-D4/Legends|R5-D4]], was almost sold to Luke Skywalker by Jawas on Tatooine, but was exchanged for [[R2-D2]], following a catastrophic failure of its motivator.<ref name="ANH">{{Film|IV}}</ref>

Aboard [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Warship/Legends|warships]], R5 units were used to monitor medical equipment such as [[life support capsule]]s.{{Fact}}

Due to their design problems, a number of R5 units were part of the population of ownerless, unwanted, and otherwise abandoned droids inhabiting [[Kligson's Moon/Legends|Kligson's Moon]].{{Fact}}

[[Rogue Squadron/Legends|Rogue Squadron]] [[Commander/Legends|commander]] [[Wedge Antilles/Legends|Wedge Antilles]] was paired with an R5 unit, R5-D2, when the unit was reformed in the early years of the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]]. Nicknamed "[[Mynock/Legends|Mynock]]" due to its terrified screeching during battle, Antilles' eventually had the droid memory wiped and renamed to [[R5-G8/Legends|R5-G8]].<ref name="EGTD" />

